body: The `vectors_per_class` is the number of support vectors per class, not the number of scores produced, I think the fact that its 6 is a coincidence. In the test code I'm running we have `vectors_per_class = {4,6}` and it emits 2 scores. LibSVM builds one v one classifiers to make predictions in multi-class spaces and that means there are `(n * (n - 1)) / 2` classifiers if there are `n` labels (i.e., all unique pairs of labels), and the LibSVM implementation returns the scores for each of those classifiers (https://github.com/cjlin1/libsvm - see `double svm_predict_values(const svm_model *model, const svm_node *x, double* dec_values)`).

FWIW the number of scores is calculated here:

https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/5da4e07daa02bbfea1edece08ba52a76cec13d13/onnxruntime/core/providers/cpu/ml/svmclassifier.cc#L159-L172

Yeah and then I think it's unfolded [here](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/8d737f977056444a307f1b7f0bcd402fba62d790/onnxruntime/core/providers/cpu/ml/ml_common.h#L494) into two classes, but I don't think it should be for an SVM that's not probabilistic as there should only be a single score. ORT isn't doing quite what the spec says either way, and the spec itself doesn't have the SVMClassifier implement LibSVM's semantics because of this one v one score vs one score per class thing.

ONNX specification is wrong about the raw scores of SVMClassifier with more than 2 classes and it should be fixed. About the case with two classes, the choice was to follow libsvm specifications or to follow the same logic as the other classifiers (LinearClassifier, ...). That's the second option which was implemented knowing that the converting libraries could change this behaviour by adding a node to extract one score column if needed. That's how it is done in skl2onnx. Is it possible to add a node  into your case or maybe replace it with a SVMRegressor?

I can definitely add a node or two to extract the appropriate information, but I was testing out the system and it seems invariant to the ordering of the label ids, so I'm not actually sure what each column is supposed to mean. Is a negative score in the first column indicating the class in `svm_model.labels[0]` or `svm_model.labels[1]`?

It would be very helpful to update the spec to explain what the output is, given it's got three modes (probabilistic gives one probability per class, binary non-probabilistic gives one score per class, multi-class non-probabilistic gives one v one scores). We'd like Tribuo to support loading in any ONNX model via ORT, and it was only when I tried to export a SVMClassifier that I realised that the output was different to the spec.

As far as possible I'm trying to have all Tribuo's ONNX exported models emit a vector of scores, one per class or dimension. The LibSVM support is my test case for using the ONNX ML operations as they produce a differently shaped output to the rest of our models. I guess I should go and port over the skl2onnx unpacking logic, I hadn't noticed it had different logic to the LibSVM exporter in onnxmltools.

A negative score in the first column should indicate class 1. The second column is the opposite of the first one. Operator [Slice](https://github.com/onnx/onnx/blob/master/docs/Operators.md#Slice) or [ArrayFeatureExtractor](https://github.com/onnx/onnx/blob/master/docs/Operators-ml.md#ai.onnx.ml.ArrayFeatureExtractor) can be used to extract one column.

Let's see what we can do to update the ONNX specifications about SVMClassifier.

scikit-learn includes libsvm source in its repository [sklearn/svm/src/libsvm](https://github.com/scikit-learn/scikit-learn/tree/main/sklearn/svm/src/libsvm). The converters in onnxmltools and scikit-learn are similar. Then scikit-learn post-processes the raw scores (here: [decision_function](https://github.com/scikit-learn/scikit-learn/blob/948582d8e8adb19c2e333bebfdd146dc563a10e9/sklearn/svm/_base.py#L757)). By default, it uses [_ovr_decision_function](https://github.com/scikit-learn/scikit-learn/blob/948582d8e8adb19c2e333bebfdd146dc563a10e9/sklearn/utils/multiclass.py#L444) and the code which implements this function in ONNX is in [support_vector_machines.py](https://github.com/onnx/sklearn-onnx/blob/master/skl2onnx/operator_converters/support_vector_machines.py#L239).

After much confusion on my part I've finally managed to get identical answers back out from an SVM trained using Tribuo in LibSVM and the same model exported into ONNX and scored via ONNX Runtime. I'm a little uncomfortable with relying on unspecified behaviour, but assuming the ONNX spec is fixed to codify what ORT does then it'll be fine.

The code is [here](https://github.com/Craigacp/tribuo/blob/libsvm-onnx/Classification/LibSVM/src/main/java/org/tribuo/classification/libsvm/LibSVMClassificationModel.java#L250), though it'll change slightly once we finish merging in a couple of larger refactors of how we emit ONNX models from Java. The voting logic was a straight translation of how sklearn2onnx works, but in the binary non-probabilistic case I had to multiply it by negative one first. I can see that in the sklearn2onnx code as well, but it's very confusing that it's necessary and I'm unclear if that's going to be part of the ONNX spec or if it's quirk of ORT. We have a gather on the end to make sure the output lines up with Tribuo's indices, rather than LibSVM's indices as those are not necessarily the same.

Thanks for the help.
Should I make a comment on https://github.com/onnx/onnx/issues/1661 to bump it? I'm unclear how to help get the ONNX spec fixed.

issue.body:
### Description
Adds ONNX export support for LibLinear and LibSVM classification and regression models. It doesn't add anomaly detection export support, we'll leave that till a future release.

The LibSVM classification export depends on the exact behaviour of ONNX Runtime as the ONNX spec for SVMClassifier is incorrect - https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/9429.

### Motivation
We'd like to export models to ONNX. Also LibSVM uses an operator from the ONNX-ML set and so is a good test of the support.
